# Event-Driven Architecture Guide

## Domain Events Overview

This project uses custom implementation of domain events to decouple modules and enable loose coupling between different parts of the system.

## Event Structure

### 1. Domain Events
```typescript
// domain/events/{entity}-{action}.event.ts
export class {Entity}{Action}Event {
  constructor(
    public readonly {entity}Id: string,
    public readonly data: {Entity}{Action}EventData,
    public readonly occurredAt: Date = new Date(),
  ) {}
}

export interface {Entity}{Action}EventData {
  // Event-specific data
  name?: string;
  description?: string;
  // ... other properties
}
```

### 2. Event Handler Interface
```typescript
// domain/events/{entity}-{action}.event.ts
export interface I{Entity}{Action}EventHandler {
  handle(event: {Entity}{Action}Event): Promise<void>;
}
```

## Implementing Event Handlers

### 1. Create Event Handler
```typescript
// infrastructure/event-handlers/{entity}-{action}.event-handler.ts
import { Injectable } from '@nestjs/common';
import { EventsHandler, IEventHandler } from '~lib/nest-event-driven';

@Injectable()
@EventsHandler({Entity}{Action}Event)
export class {Entity}{Action}EventHandler implements IEventHandler<{Entity}{Action}Event> {
  constructor(
    @Inject(DiToken.SOME_SERVICE)
    private readonly someService: ISomeService,
  ) {}

  async handle(event: {Entity}{Action}Event): Promise<void> {
    const { {entity}Id, data } = event;
    
    // Handle the event
    await this.someService.process{Action}({entity}Id, data);
  }
}
```

### 2. Register Event Handler in Module
```typescript
@Module({
  providers: [
    // ... other providers
    {Entity}{Action}EventHandler,
  ],
})
export class {ModuleName}Module {}
```

## Dispatching Events

### 1. In Use Cases (Automatic)
```typescript
// Events are automatically dispatched after successful command execution
@Injectable()
export class Create{Entity}UseCase extends Command<Create{Entity}Dto, {Entity}> {
  constructor(
    @Inject(DiToken.{ENTITY}_REPOSITORY)
    private readonly {entity}Repository: I{Entity}Repository,
  ) {
    super();
  }

  protected async implementation(): Promise<{Entity}> {
    const {entity} = {Entity}.builder(this._input.name).build();
    
    const created{Entity} = await this.{entity}Repository.create({entity});
    
    // Event is automatically dispatched by base Command class, you need to only register an event
    this._eventDispatcher.registerEvent(
      new {Entity}CreateEvent({
        invitationId: invitation.id,
      }),
    );
    
    return created{Entity};
  }
}
```

### 2. Manual Event Dispatching (not recommended, try to always do it with Command class)
```typescript
@Injectable()
export class {Entity}Service {
  constructor(
    @Inject(BaseToken.EVENT_DISPATCHER)
    private readonly eventDispatcher: IEventDispatcher,
  ) {}

  async processSomething(): Promise<void> {
    // ... business logic
    
    // Manually dispatch event
    this.eventDispatcher.dispatch(new {Entity}ProcessedEvent(entityId, data));
  }
}
```

## Event Handler Examples

### 1. Company Logo Uploaded Event
```typescript
@Injectable()
@EventsHandler(CompanyLogoUploadedEvent)
export class CompanyLogoUploadedEventHandler implements IEventHandler<CompanyLogoUploadedEvent> {
  constructor(
    @Inject(CompaniesDiToken.COMPANY_REPOSITORY)
    private readonly companyRepository: ICompanyRepository,
  ) {}

  async handle(event: CompanyLogoUploadedEvent): Promise<void> {
    const { companyId, logoUrl } = event;
    
    // Update company with new logo
    await this.companyRepository.updateLogo(companyId, logoUrl);
  }
}
```

## Cross-Module Communication

### 1. Module A Dispatches Event
```typescript
// In auth module
@Injectable()
export class UserRegisteredUseCase extends Command<UserRegistrationDto, User> {
  protected async implementation(): Promise<User> {
    // ... user creation logic
    
    // Dispatch event that other modules can listen to (dispatches automatically in Command class)
    this._eventDispatcher.registerEvent(new UserRegisteredEvent(user.id, {
      email: user.email,
      role: user.role,
    }));
    
    return user;
  }
}
```

### 2. Module B Handles Event
```typescript
// In email module
@Injectable()
@EventsHandler(UserRegisteredEvent)
export class UserRegisteredEventHandler implements IEventHandler<UserRegisteredEvent> {
  constructor(
    @Inject(EmailDiToken.WELCOME_EMAIL_SERVICE)
    private readonly welcomeEmailService: IWelcomeEmailService,
  ) {}

  async handle(event: UserRegisteredEvent): Promise<void> {
    const { userId, data } = event;
    
    // Send welcome email
    await this.welcomeEmailService.sendWelcomeEmail(userId, data.email);
  }
}
```

## Best Practices

### 1. Event Naming
- Use past tense: `CompanyCreatedEvent`, `UserUpdatedEvent`
- Be descriptive about what happened
- Include relevant data in the event

### 2. Event Data
- Keep events lightweight
- Include only necessary data
- Avoid including entire entities (use IDs instead)

### 3. Event Handler Responsibilities
- Keep handlers focused on single responsibility
- Avoid complex business logic in handlers
- Use handlers for side effects and cross-module communication

### 4. Error Handling
- Event handlers should handle their own errors
- Failed event handling shouldn't break the main flow
- Log errors appropriately

## Event Flow

1. **Command Execution**: Use case executes business logic
2. **Event Creation**: Domain event is created with relevant data
3. **Event Dispatch**: Event is dispatched to event bus
4. **Event Handling**: Registered event handlers process the event
5. **Side Effects**: Handlers perform necessary side effects
6. **Cross-Module Communication**: Modules react to events from other modules
